      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, if the reactance were higher, say $80\\ \\Omega$, the total impedance would definitely increase, which would cause the current to decrease. The impedance calculation would become $Z = \\sqrt{50^2 + 80^2} = \\sqrt{2500 + 6400} = \\sqrt{8900} \\approx 94.34\\ \\Omega$. This higher impedance means less current flows from the $120\\text{ V}$ source.\n\nFurthermore, the combination of resistance and reactance absolutely affects the phase angle ($\\phi$), which tells you how much the voltage and current are out of sync. The phase angle is found using $\\tan(\\phi) = X_L / R$, so $\\phi = \\arctan(80/50) = \\arctan(1.6) \\approx 57.99^\\circ$. A higher reactance means a larger phase angle, indicating the current lags the voltage more significantly.\n\n*(This is a bit more complex than the simple calculation, but it's a fundamental concept in AC circuits!)*\n\n*(I've been thinking about how a bigger inductor would make the current flow",
